This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with object detection and shape prediction. The use of a denoising convolutional auto-encoder also suggests a focus on deep learning techniques, which are commonly used in computer vision research. 

The paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it involves training a network to regress directly to encoded shape vectors. 

The artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category is also a possibility as the paper involves developing a network that can reason about higher-order concepts such as view similarity, pose variation, and occlusion. 

The neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category is another possibility as the paper involves training a network using deep learning techniques. 

Finally, the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category is a possibility as the paper may have applications in robotics, particularly in object detection and recognition tasks.
